title.narrative: MATERNAL AND CHILD NUTRITION AND IMMUNIZATION

description.narrative: Increased access to and use of high-impact nutrition interventions among pregnant and lactating women and boys and girls under five to reduce chronic malnutrition, particularly in the most deprived provinces, including in emergency- prone areas., which contributes to Adolescent Health And Nutrition, Child Health, Community-Based Management Of Acute Malnutrition, Health And Emergencies, Immunization, Infant And Young Child Feeding, Maternal And Newborn Health, Nutrition And Emergencies, Polio Eradication, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2019, the most vulnerable children, boys, girls, adolescents and women of child bearing age will have reduced reported common preventable illnesses and disease conditions

description.narrative: In 2019, 663 community health workers and 365 health staff had their knowledge increased and skills enhanced to provide quality care of children with acute malnutrition and screened 186,338 children under five for malnutrition, referred and treated, 19,143 children with moderate acute malnutrition and 6,267 children with severe acute malnutrition in 28 inpatient facilities and 210 outpatient treatment programme sites in 23 municipalities of Cunene, Huila, Bie, and Namibe provinces. | Status:Met | As-of Date:04/07/2019
